<section xml:id="dirichlet-characters" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Dirichlet Characters and L-Functions</title>

  <p> Let <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m> . Let <m>\chi:(\mathbb{Z}/N\mathbb{Z})^{\times} \to \mathbb{C}^{\times}</m> be a primitive dirichlet character (i.e it doesn't factor through <m>(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z})^{\times}</m>) through any proper divisor <m>N</m>. 
  We can define the L-function of <m>\chi</m> as follows: </p>
  <p>
    <m> L(s,\chi) = \sum_{n = 1}^{\infty} \frac{\chi(n)}{n^s} = \prod_{p \mid N} \left( 1 - \frac{\chi(p)}{p^s} \right)^{-1} \prod_{p \nmid N} \left( 1 - \frac{\chi(p)}{p^s} \right)^{-1} </m>
  </p>
  <p>
    This series has two interesting properties:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          It converges absolutely and uniformly for <m>\text{Re}(s) \geq 1 + \epsilon</m> for any fixed <m>\epsilon > 0</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          It has an analytic continuation to the entire complex plane except when <m>N = 1, \chi = \unicode{x1D7D9}</m> in which case it has a meromorphic continuation with a simple pole (<m> s = 1, \text{res} = 1</m>).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  The zeta function satisfies a few functional equations which are stated below (without proofs)
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\Lambda(\chi,s) = (\frac{\pi}{N})^{-\frac{1}{2}(s + \sigma)}\Gamma(\frac{1}{2}(s + \sigma))L(\chi,s)</m> 

      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\Lambda(\chi,s) = \frac{\tau(x)}{i^{\sigma}N^{\frac{1}{2}}}\Lambda(\overline{\chi},1-s)</m>

      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    where we have
  </p> 
  <p>
    <m>
      \sigma = \begin{cases}
                0 \:\: \text{if } \chi(-1) = 1 \\
                1 \:\: \text{if } \chi(-1) = -1
                \end{cases}
    </m>
  </p>
  <p>
    and the Gauss Sum
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>\tau(x) = \sum_{m = 1}^N \chi(m) e^{\frac{2\pi i m}{N}}</m> (Gauss Sum)
  </p>
  <p>and clearly <m>|\tau(x)| = \sqrt{N}</m></p>.
  <p>
    As a consequence we have
  </p>
  <p>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>L(\chi,1-n) = 0 \:\: \text{if} \:\: \chi(-1) \neq (-1)^n</m>
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <m>L(\chi,1 - n) \neq 0 \:\: \text{if} \:\: \chi(-1) = (-1)^n</m>
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p>
    where <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    An important fact relating L-functions to Bernoulli numbers is
  </p>
  <p>
    for <m>n \geq 0, \:\: \chi(-1) = (-1)^n</m> we have
    <p>
      <m>L(\chi,1-n) = -\frac{B_{n,\chi}}{n}</m> where
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\sum_{n = 0}^{\infty} \frac{B_{n,\chi}}{n1}t^n = \sum_{a = 1}^{N} \frac{\chi(a)te^{at}}{e^{Nt} - 1}</m>(Formal identity)
    </p>
    <p>
      In particular, <m>L(\chi,1-n) \in \mathbb{Q}(\chi) = \text{ field obtained by adjoining the values of }\chi\text{ to }\mathbb{Q}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
      , we end up with algebraic numbers.
    </p>
  </p>
  <subsection>
    <title>An Important Example</title>
    We give a few examples
  <p>
    For <m>\chi(-1) = -1</m>,
    <p>
      <m>L(\chi,0) = -\frac{1}{N}\sum_{a = 1}^{N} \chi(a)a</m>
    </p>
  </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
  <title>Another Example</title>
  <p>
    Let <m>p</m> be an odd prime, <m>\zeta_p</m> be primitive <m>p^{\text{th}}</m>-root of unity.
  </p>
  <p>
    We know that
  </p> 
  <p>
    <m>G = \text{Gal}(\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p)/\mathbb{Q}) \cong (\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z})^{\times}</m> where we have <m>\sigma \longmapsto a, \ni \sigma(\zeta_p) = \zeta_p^a</m>
  </p>
  </subsection>

  



</section>